{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":918,"record_hash":"sha256:87281811d6f4e4e4337e76df0fb22f0d9a24fa274ddd820ce6ea0cf105ec550d","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:16:34.105Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 343c23\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 683\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood future PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nFor v1, a reviewer starts from a GitHub pull request URL and opens the matching\nGitButler-owned Agent Trail URL by replacing the host. The server builds or\nloads a generated snapshot for that public pull request.\n\nExplicit PR description links, bot comments, check-run details links, or GitHub\napp panels can come later as distribution channels. They are not required for\nthe first build.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. Transcript records are the\nunderlying evidence, but the review experience should be organized around\nhelping a reviewer understand the change.\n  `but-agentlog-read` or `but-agenttrail-core` crate that owns target\n  construction, verified lookup, match reasons, and public projections\n\nExample shape:\n\n```toml\nbut-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n```\n\nThe important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\nsnapshot, visibility, and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation\nshould stay in `but-agentlog`.\n\nBuild may start for public repos and publicly fetchable metadata. Private repo,\nteam, explicit-share, and richer publication flows are later work.\n\n- same users who can view the pull request\n- explicit share link recipients\n\nDo not build private repository policy into v1.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no claim that agent sessions authored the pull request\n- no full transcript dump as the main experience\n- no copying transcript records onto pull request targets\n- no hosted-page or Forge-specific storage payloads inside `but-agentlog`\n- no magic generated summary as the source of truth\n- no private repository support in v1\n- no fork pull request support in v1\n- no GitHub OAuth or GitButler workspace auth in v1\n- no configurable metadata remotes or arbitrary metadata refs in v1\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:16:34.105Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}